# 1. Pottery basics
E.append({'id':'l4-technology-pottery-basics','title':'Pottery Basics — Hand-Building & Pit Firing','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'technology','tags':['pottery','ceramics','clay','firing'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l3-materials-clay-identification'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Pottery provides waterproof containers for cooking, storage, and transport. Hand-building techniques (pinch, coil, slab) require no wheel. Pit firing (campfire or earth kiln) achieves temps needed to harden clay. Primitive pottery is porous but functional.','warnings':['Pottery can crack or explode during firing if dried improperly or contains air bubbles','Pit-fired pottery is porous - not fully waterproof unless sealed with pitch or oil','Large thick pieces are prone to cracking - start small and thin'],'steps':['CLAY PREP: Use tested clay (see clay ID entry). Wedge clay (knead like dough) to remove air bubbles. Add temper (sand 10-20 percent).','HAND-BUILDING: PINCH POT - Start with ball, press thumb into center, pinch walls thin while rotating. COIL - Roll clay into ropes, stack in spiral, smooth joins. SLAB - Flatten clay, cut shapes, join edges. Start with simple bowl or cup.','DRYING: CRITICAL. Dry SLOWLY (days to weeks) in shade. Fast drying causes cracks. Cover with plastic, uncover for few hours daily. Bone dry = ready to fire (no cool feel, very light).','PIT FIRING: Dig shallow pit. Build fire, let burn to coals. Place dried pottery in coals. Cover with more fuel (wood, dung). Fire for 4-8 hours. Let cool completely overnight. Pottery should be hard, ring when tapped. If cracked, try again with slower drying or more temper.','USES: Cooking (set in coals, not direct flame). Water storage (seal with pine pitch). Food storage (dry goods).']})

# 2. Blacksmithing basics
E.append({'id':'l3-metalwork-blacksmith-basics','title':'Blacksmithing Basics — Forge, Anvil, First Projects','category':'L3_materials_chemistry','subtopic':'materials','tags':['blacksmithing','forge','metal','iron'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l3-materials-wood-properties-guide'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Blacksmithing shapes iron and steel by heating and hammering. Essential for making durable tools (knives, axes, nails, hinges). Requires forge (high-temp fire), anvil (striking surface), hammer, tongs. Learning curve but invaluable long-term skill.','warnings':['Forge temps (1000-1400C) cause severe burns - use long tongs and leather protection','Sparks and scale (metal flakes) can injure eyes - wear safety glasses','Hot metal looks identical to cool metal - never touch until confirmed cool','Coal/charcoal forges produce carbon monoxide - work outdoors or with ventilation'],'steps':['FORGE: Fireproof box with air source (bellows or hand-crank blower). Fuel: charcoal or coal. Heat metal to yellow-orange glow (forging temp).','ANVIL: Heavy steel block (or large flat rock as substitute). Hardened face for hammering.','FIRST PROJECT - HOOK: (1) Heat end of iron rod. (2) Hammer flat (draw out). (3) Bend into hook shape (over anvil edge). (4) Reheat as needed. Simple but useful.','SKILLS: Heating, hammer control, bending, cutting (chisel), punching holes, welding (joining two pieces). Start simple, practice.','TOOLS TO MAKE: Nails (cut and taper rod), knives (flatten, sharpen, harden), axes, hinges, chains.']})

# 3-10: Food & Agriculture
E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-chicken-keeping','title':'Chicken Keeping — Eggs, Meat, & Backyard Flock','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['chickens','poultry','eggs','homestead'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-food-safety'],'related_entries':['l2-food-wild-turkey-processing'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Chickens are the easiest livestock. Produce eggs daily, meat when butchered. Require shelter, feed (grain or forage), water. Hens lay without rooster (unfertilized eggs). 3-6 hens provide eggs for small family.','warnings':['Predators (foxes, hawks, raccoons) kill chickens - secure coop required','Chickens carry Salmonella - wash hands after handling','Roosters are loud - may anger neighbors','Feeding only scraps produces weak eggs - need protein and calcium'],'steps':['HOUSING: Coop with nest boxes, roosts, protection from predators and weather. 4 sq ft per bird inside, 10 sq ft outdoor run.','FEEDING: Layer pellets (commercial) or mixed grains (wheat, corn) + protein (insects, worms, meat scraps) + calcium (crushed shells, oyster shell). Free-range chickens forage 50 percent of diet.','EGGS: Hens lay 200-300 eggs per year (peak 1-3 years old, decline after). Collect daily. Unwashed eggs last weeks at room temp.','MEAT: Butcher roosters or old hens. Processing same as wild turkey (see entry).','DISEASES: Keep coop clean, dry, well-ventilated. Separate sick birds. Most backyard flocks are healthy if managed well.']})

E.append({'id':'l2-food-preservation-comprehensive','title':'Food Preservation Methods — Drying, Smoking, Salting, Fermenting','category':'L2_food_biology','subtopic':'food_preparation','tags':['food-preservation','smoking','salting','drying','fermenting'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-food-safety','cdc-food-safety'],'related_entries':['l2-food-meat-jerky','l2-food-fermentation'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Without refrigeration, food spoils rapidly. Preservation methods remove water or alter chemistry to prevent bacterial growth. Drying, smoking, salting, fermenting, and cold storage (root cellar) allow long-term food storage.','warnings':['Improperly preserved food causes botulism, salmonella, mold poisoning - follow guidelines strictly','Canning requires pressure canner for low-acid foods - improper canning is deadly','Smoked meat still requires cool dry storage - smoking alone does not prevent all spoilage'],'steps':['DRYING (removes water, bacteria cannot grow): SUN DRY - thin slices on racks, 3-5 days hot sun, cover at night. SMOKE DRY - hang in smokehouse, cool smoke for days. OVEN DRY - low temp (60C) for hours. Fully dried = hard, no moisture when squeezed. Store in airtight container. Rehydrate before eating.','SMOKING (drying + flavor + some preservation): Cold smoke (20-30C, days) for flavor + drying. Hot smoke (60-80C, hours) cooks and dries. Smoke from hardwoods (no pine - creosote). Hang meat/fish in smokehouse or improvised smoking chamber.','SALTING (salt draws out water, creates hostile environment): Pack meat/fish in salt (complete coverage). Leave 1-2 weeks. Rinse excess salt. Hang to dry. Result: very salty, lasts months. Soak in water before cooking (removes excess salt).','FERMENTING (beneficial bacteria/yeast prevent spoilage): Sauerkraut (cabbage + salt), kimchi, pickles (vegetables in brine), beer, wine. Lactic acid bacteria preserve food. See fermentation entry.','ROOT CELLAR (cold storage, 0-10C): Dig underground room or use natural cave. Cool temps slow spoilage. Store root vegetables (potatoes, carrots, beets), apples, cured meat, cheese. Humidity 80-90 percent.','ROTATION: Eat oldest food first. Check stored food monthly for mold, spoilage.']})

