# Navigation & weather
E.append({'id':'l1-navigation-without-compass','title':'Navigation Without Compass — Sun, Stars, Natural Signs','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'navigation','tags':['navigation','sun','stars','wayfinding'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-navigation-star-navigation'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Compass and GPS fail. Natural navigation uses sun, stars, moss, tree growth, wind patterns. Sun rises east, sets west. North Star (Polaris) marks true north. Southern Cross points south. Moss grows on north side of trees in northern hemisphere (usually).','warnings':['Moss on trees is unreliable in dense forests or wet climates','Cloud cover prevents sun/star navigation','Natural navigation provides direction only - still need map or terrain knowledge'],'steps':['SUN METHOD: Sun rises east, sets west. At noon, sun is due south (northern hemisphere) or due north (southern hemisphere). Shadow-stick method: Plant stick upright, mark shadow tip, wait 15 min, mark again. Line between marks runs east-west.','NORTH STAR (Polaris): Find Big Dipper, follow pointer stars to Polaris (bright star). Polaris marks true north. Northern hemisphere only.','SOUTHERN CROSS: Find Southern Cross constellation, extend long axis 4.5x its length - that point is south. Southern hemisphere only.','MOSS: Grows thicker on north side of trees (northern hemisphere) due to less sun. Unreliable - check multiple trees.','PREVAILING WINDS: Learn dominant wind direction for region. Wind-shaped trees lean away from prevailing wind.']})

E.append({'id':'l1-weather-prediction-field','title':'Weather Prediction — Cloud Types & Natural Signs','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'weather','tags':['weather','clouds','forecasting','survival'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-shelter-lightning-safety'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Predicting weather without forecast: observe clouds, wind shifts, air pressure signs, animal behavior. High wispy clouds (cirrus) indicate weather change in 24 hours. Darkening clouds = storm approaching. Sudden wind shift = front moving through.','warnings':['Weather signs are general trends - not precise forecasts','Mountain and coastal weather is unpredictable','Severe weather can develop rapidly (thunderstorms, tornadoes) - seek shelter at first signs'],'steps':['CLOUDS: Cirrus (high wispy) - weather change coming. Cumulus (puffy white) - fair weather if morning, storms if build tall in afternoon. Cumulonimbus (towering dark) - thunderstorms imminent. Stratus (low gray sheet) - drizzle or snow.','WIND: Steady wind from one direction = stable weather. Sudden shift or swirling = front approaching (expect rain/storms).','PRESSURE SIGNS: Difficulty starting fire (damp air, low pressure) = rain coming. Clear sharp distant views = high pressure, fair weather. Hazy distant views = moisture in air, rain possible.','ANIMAL BEHAVIOR: Birds flying low = low pressure, rain coming. Insects swarm = fair weather. Cattle lying down = rain coming (folklore, somewhat reliable).','RED SKY: Red sky at morning, sailors take warning (rain coming). Red sky at night, sailors delight (fair weather). Based on sunset light through moisture.']})

# Shelter & survival
E.append({'id':'l1-shelter-primitive-types','title':'Primitive Shelter Types — Debris Hut, Lean-To, A-Frame','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'shelter','tags':['shelter','primitive','emergency','debris-hut'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-shelter-tarp-configurations'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Emergency shelters from natural materials. Debris hut (insulated cocoon), lean-to (rain protection), A-frame (simple roof). Prioritize insulation and wind/rain protection. Takes 2-6 hours to build depending on type.','warnings':['Inadequate insulation causes hypothermia even if shelter keeps rain off','Build shelter BEFORE dark - takes longer than expected','Site selection matters - avoid low spots (cold air pools), widow-makers (dead branches overhead)'],'steps':['DEBRIS HUT: (1) Ridge pole 8-10 ft long, one end on ground, other on stump/fork 3 ft high. (2) Lean ribs (sticks) against both sides. (3) Pile leaves/grass/debris 2-3 ft thick over frame. (4) Crawl inside (tight fit - body heat warms space). Best insulation.','LEAN-TO: (1) Horizontal ridge pole between two trees, 4-5 ft high. (2) Lean poles against ridge at 45 degrees. (3) Cover with bark, branches, leaves. (4) Build fire in front (reflects heat). Rain protection, less insulation.','A-FRAME: (1) Ridge pole on two forked sticks. (2) Lean poles on both sides (like tent). (3) Cover with bark/branches/debris. (4) Enclosed on three sides. Moderate insulation and protection.']})

E.append({'id':'l2-food-trap-making-comprehensive','title':'Trap & Snare Making — Passive Hunting Techniques','category':'L2_food_biology','subtopic':'hunting_fishing','tags':['traps','snares','hunting','survival'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l2-food-rabbit-squirrel-processing'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Traps catch game while you sleep or work. Snares (wire loops that tighten), deadfalls (weight crushes animal), pit traps. Set multiple traps (increase odds). Check daily. Illegal in most areas except survival.','warnings':['Traps are indiscriminate - can catch pets, endangered species, or injure humans','Check legality - trapping is illegal in many jurisdictions','Trapped animals may be injured and dangerous when you approach','Set traps away from trails to avoid human encounters'],'steps':['SNARE: Wire loop on game trail. Animal walks through, loop tightens around neck/body. SETUP: (1) Bend sapling or use spring pole. (2) Attach wire loop to trigger stick. (3) Animal disturbs trigger, sapling springs up, tightens loop. Check for rabbit, squirrel.','DEADFALL: Heavy rock balanced on trigger sticks. Animal takes bait, trigger releases, rock crushes animal. Simple but requires precise trigger. Small game only.','FIGURE-4 DEADFALL: Three sticks form Figure-4 shape. Bait on one stick. Animal pulls bait, trigger collapses, rock falls. Learn to carve notches for interlocking sticks.','PIT TRAP: Dig hole, cover with sticks and leaves (concealment). Large game falls in. Very labor-intensive. Add sharpened stakes at bottom (dangerous).','SET LOCATION: Game trails (look for tracks, droppings, worn paths). Near water, feeding areas, dens. Set 10+ traps (most will fail).']})

# More food & skills
E.append({'id':'l2-food-fishing-methods','title':'Fishing Methods — Pole, Net, Trap, Spear','category':'L2_food_biology','subtopic':'hunting_fishing','tags':['fishing','net','spear','trap','survival'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l2-fish-trout-identification'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Multiple fishing methods increase success. Pole fishing (most common), nets (efficient for small fish), traps (passive), spears (requires skill). Use local bait (worms, insects, small fish).','warnings':['Regulations vary - fishing may require license even in survival','Some fish are toxic (pufferfish, certain tropical species) - research local species','Fishing in polluted water produces contaminated fish'],'steps':['POLE: Line, hook, bait. Cast into likely spots (near structure, shaded pools). Patience.','GILL NET: Net stretched across stream. Fish swim into it, gills caught in mesh. Passive, effective. Illegal in many areas.','FISH TRAP: Funnel-shaped basket or rock enclosure. Fish enter, cannot find exit. Set in stream, check daily.','SPEAR: Sharpened stick or multi-pronged spear. Wade in shallow water, strike fish. Aim low (refraction makes fish appear higher than actual position).','BAIT: Worms (dig in moist soil), insects (grasshoppers, beetles), small fish (minnows), meat scraps, dough balls.']})

E.append({'id':'l2-food-caching-storage','title':'Food Caching — Long-Term Storage Without Refrigeration','category':'L2_food_biology','subtopic':'food_preparation','tags':['food-storage','caching','preservation','root-cellar'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-food-safety'],'related_entries':['l2-food-preservation-comprehensive'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Without refrigeration, use cool dry storage, underground caches, hanging (air circulation), and separation by type. Root cellars (underground, 0-10C) store root vegetables, apples months. Grain in sealed containers protects from rodents, moisture.','warnings':['Rodents destroy food - use sealed metal or glass containers','Moisture causes mold - keep storage area dry','Some foods emit ethylene gas (apples) which spoils nearby foods - store separately','Check stored food regularly for spoilage'],'steps':['ROOT CELLAR: Dig into hillside or underground (below frost line). Insulated door, vent for air circulation. Maintains 0-10C year-round. Store potatoes, carrots, beets, apples, cured meat.','UNDERGROUND CACHE: Dig hole, line with bark/plastic. Store food in sealed containers. Cover with dirt, mark location. Protects from animals. Check for moisture.','HANGING: Suspend food from rafters (air circulates, rodents cannot reach). Good for cured meat, dried herbs, onions/garlic braids.','GRAIN STORAGE: Sealed metal drums or glass jars. Add bay leaves (repels insects). Cool dry location. Wheat, rice, beans last years if dry.','SEPARATION: Store by type and smell. Strong-smelling foods (onions, fish) separate from mild (grains). Apples separate from other produce (ethylene gas).']})

# More agriculture
E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-garden-planning','title':'Vegetable Garden Planning — Layout, Crop Selection, Rotation','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['gardening','crops','vegetables','planning'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-plants-database'],'related_entries':['l4-agriculture-season-planning','l4-agriculture-seed-saving'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Plan garden for continuous harvest and soil health. Crop rotation prevents disease. Succession planting (plant every 2 weeks) provides steady supply. Prioritize high-calorie, storable crops (potatoes, beans, squash). Consider climate and season length.','warnings':['Gardening is harder than it looks - expect failures first year','Local climate matters - not all crops grow everywhere','Pests and disease can destroy entire crop - plan for loss'],'steps':['CROP SELECTION: STAPLES (high calorie, stores well): Potatoes, beans, squash, corn, wheat. VEGETABLES (nutrition): Tomatoes, carrots, lettuce, cabbage, onions. QUICK (harvest in weeks): Radishes, lettuce, spinach. LONG SEASON (months): Tomatoes, peppers, squash.','LAYOUT: Rows or beds. Tall plants (corn) on north side (do not shade shorter plants). Climbing plants (beans, peas) on trellis. Wide spacing (reduces disease but lower yield).','CROP ROTATION: Do not plant same family in same spot year after year (disease builds up). Rotate: Year 1 - tomatoes. Year 2 - beans. Year 3 - root vegetables. Year 4 - greens.','SUCCESSION PLANTING: Plant lettuce every 2 weeks (continuous harvest). Plant beans 3 times per season.','CALENDAR: Know frost dates. Plant cool-season crops (lettuce, peas) early spring and fall. Warm-season (tomatoes, peppers) after last frost.']})

E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-seed-saving','title':'Seed Saving — Heirloom Varieties & Self-Sufficiency','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['seeds','heirloom','saving','self-sufficiency'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-plants-database'],'related_entries':['l4-agriculture-garden-planning'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Save seeds from harvest to plant next year (self-sufficiency). Heirloom varieties (open-pollinated) produce true-to-type seeds. Hybrid seeds do not. Dry seeds thoroughly, store cool and dry. Test germination before spring.','warnings':['Hybrid seeds (F1) do not produce true offspring - save only heirloom/open-pollinated varieties','Wet seeds mold - dry completely before storage','Old seeds lose viability - test germination rate before planting','Some plants cross-pollinate easily (squash) - isolate varieties to maintain purity'],'steps':['SELECTING PLANTS: Choose healthiest, most productive plants for seed saving. Let fruit fully ripen on plant.','DRY SEEDS: Tomatoes, peppers - ferment pulp 3 days, rinse, dry. Beans, peas - let pods dry on plant, shell. Squash - scoop seeds, rinse, dry. Lettuce - let bolt (flower), collect seeds from dried seed heads.','STORAGE: Store in paper envelopes or glass jars. Label variety and year. Keep cool (10-15C), dry, dark. Seeds last 2-5 years (varies by species).','GERMINATION TEST: Before planting season, test 10 seeds on damp paper towel. Count how many sprout. 70 percent+ is good. Low rate = plant extra to compensate.','HEIRLOOM VARIETIES: Old non-hybrid varieties (passed down generations). Produce consistent seeds. Flavor often better than hybrids but lower yield. Preserve genetic diversity.']})

E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-composting','title':'Composting — Building Soil Fertility','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['compost','soil','fertility','organic-matter'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['usda-plants-database'],'related_entries':['l4-agriculture-garden-planning'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Compost turns organic waste (kitchen scraps, leaves, manure) into rich soil amendment. Improves soil structure, adds nutrients, feeds soil life. Hot composting (fast, 2-3 months) vs cold composting (slow, 6-12 months). Balance green (nitrogen) and brown (carbon) materials.','warnings':['Compost pile can smell if too wet or too much green material','Meat, dairy, oils attract pests - do not compost (or use hot composting only)','Diseased plant material can spread disease - do not compost or use hot composting (kills pathogens)'],'steps':['MATERIALS: GREEN (nitrogen - wet, fresh): kitchen scraps (vegetables, fruit), grass clippings, fresh manure, green leaves. BROWN (carbon - dry): dead leaves, straw, wood chips, cardboard. RATIO: 2-3 parts brown to 1 part green (by volume).','HOT COMPOSTING: (1) Build pile 3x3x3 feet minimum (needs mass to heat up). (2) Layer green and brown. (3) Water until damp (like wrung-out sponge). (4) Turn pile weekly (adds oxygen). (5) Pile heats to 55-65C (kills weed seeds, pathogens). (6) Ready in 2-3 months (dark, crumbly, earthy smell).','COLD COMPOSTING: Pile materials, leave alone. Decomposes slowly (6-12 months+). Less work but does not kill weed seeds.','TROUBLESHOOTING: SMELLS BAD - Too wet or too much green. Add brown material, turn pile. TOO DRY - Add water and green material. NOT HEATING - Too small (add more material) or needs turning.','USING COMPOST: Spread 2-4 inches on garden beds. Mix into soil. Top-dress around plants. Mulch. Improves any soil (clay, sand, depleted).']})

# More skills
E.append({'id':'l1-fire-friction-methods','title':'Fire by Friction — Bow Drill, Hand Drill, Fire Plow','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'fire','tags':['fire','friction','primitive','bow-drill'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-fire-ferro-rod'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Creating fire by friction - spinning wood against wood generates heat (ember). Methods: bow drill (easiest), hand drill (hardest), fire plow. Requires dry softwoods, proper technique, patience. Success rate low for beginners but achievable with practice.','warnings':['Friction fire is extremely difficult and time-consuming - use modern methods when available','Requires bone-dry wood - impossible in rain or high humidity','Blisters on hands are common with hand drill','Friction methods rarely work first try - practice before you need it'],'steps':['BOW DRILL: (1) PARTS: Fireboard (flat softwood), spindle (round stick), bow (curved stick with cordage), handhold (stone or wood with socket). (2) Cut V-notch in fireboard (catches coal). (3) Bow string wrapped once around spindle. (4) Spindle vertical on fireboard, handhold on top. (5) Bow back and forth (spins spindle). (6) Downward pressure + speed = smoke, then ember in notch. (7) Transfer ember to tinder bundle, blow gently.','WOOD SELECTION: Dry softwoods work best. Cedar, cottonwood, willow, basswood. Spindle and fireboard should be same or similar hardness.','HAND DRILL: No bow - spin spindle between palms. Very difficult (blisters). Use long thin spindle, downward pressure as you spin.','FIRE PLOW: Rub hardwood stick in groove on softwood board. Creates ember at end of groove. Rare technique.']})

E.append({'id':'l1-knots-comprehensive','title':'Essential Knots — Bowline, Clove Hitch, Taut-Line, Figure-8','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'skills','tags':['knots','rope','cordage','survival'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l3-materials-rope-making'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'A dozen knots cover 90 percent of needs. Bowline (fixed loop), clove hitch (attach to pole), taut-line hitch (adjustable loop), figure-8 (stopper knot), square knot (join ropes). Practice until you can tie in dark.','warnings':['Wrong knot for application can fail catastrophically','Some knots weaken rope (up to 50 percent strength loss)','Wet knots are harder to untie - leave slack when possible'],'steps':['BOWLINE: Fixed loop (does not slip). Climbing, rescue, securing loads. Rabbit comes out of hole, around tree, back in hole.','CLOVE HITCH: Attach rope to pole or tree. Quick, adjustable. Two wraps, second crosses over first.','TAUT-LINE HITCH: Adjustable loop. Tent guylines. Grips under load, slides when slack.','FIGURE-8: Stopper knot (prevents rope from sliding through hole). Climbing, securing end of rope.','SQUARE KNOT: Join two ropes of same diameter. Left over right, right over left. NOT for climbing (can slip under load).','SHEET BEND: Join two ropes of different diameters. Better than square knot for unequal ropes.','PRUSIK: Friction hitch slides up rope but grips under load. Climbing safety, hauling.','TRUCKER HITCH: Mechanical advantage for tightening loads. Creates 3:1 pulley. Securing cargo.']})

# Desert & extreme environments
E.append({'id':'l1-survival-desert-comprehensive','title':'Desert Survival — Water, Heat, Navigation, Hazards','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'environment','tags':['desert','heat','dehydration','survival'],'region_relevance':['desert'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-water-desert-sources','l1-strategy-environment-profiles'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Desert survival priorities: water, shade, avoiding heat stress. Dehydration kills fast in desert heat (130F+). Travel at night, rest in shade by day. Conserve water - do not ration (drink when thirsty). Signal for rescue. Many desert hazards (snakes, scorpions, flash floods).','warnings':['Dehydration symptoms (dark urine, dizziness, confusion) mean you are already in danger','Desert temperatures swing 40-50F between day and night - prepare for both extremes','Flash floods kill more people in deserts than dehydration - avoid washes during rain'],'steps':['WATER: Priority 1. Find water sources (see entry) or carry enough. Minimum 1 gallon per day (more if active). Do NOT ration water - drink when thirsty. Body needs water to cool itself.','SHADE: Avoid midday heat (10am-4pm). Rest in shade or improvised shelter (tarp, rock overhang, dig trench and cover). Travel early morning, evening, night.','CLOTHING: Cover all skin (sun protection, reduces sweat evaporation). Light-colored loose clothing. Head covering essential (40 percent heat loss from head).','SIGNALING: Open terrain = high visibility. Use mirror, fire, bright clothing. Stay visible (ridgelines, clearings).','HAZARDS: Snakes and scorpions hide in shade (shake out boots, check before sitting). Flash floods in washes (move to high ground if rain visible). Quicksand (rare but possible near dry lakes).']})

E.append({'id':'l1-survival-jungle-basics','title':'Jungle Survival — Water, Shelter, Navigation, Disease','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'environment','tags':['jungle','tropical','rainforest','survival'],'region_relevance':['tropical'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l1-strategy-environment-profiles'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Jungle survival challenges: abundant water (but often contaminated), dense vegetation (slow travel, poor visibility), high heat and humidity (exhaustion, heat rash), disease (malaria, dengue, infections), dangerous animals. Priorities: water purification, dry shelter, avoiding infections.','warnings':['Jungle water is often contaminated with parasites - purify all water','Fungal infections and foot rot develop quickly in constant moisture - keep feet dry','Many jungle plants and animals are toxic - do not eat unknown species','Malaria and dengue mosquitoes are deadly - prevent bites'],'steps':['WATER: Abundant but contaminated. Boil, filter, or treat. Collect rainwater (cleanest). Vines may have drinkable water (cut high, let drain into container - not all vines are safe).','SHELTER: Keep dry (constant rain). Elevated platform (off wet ground, away from insects). Thatched roof (palm fronds, large leaves). Hammock if available.','TRAVEL: Extremely slow (dense vegetation). Use machete or follow animal trails, streams. Navigation difficult (no landmarks, canopy blocks sun/stars). Use compass.','FIRE: Hard to start (everything is wet). Find dry tinder under bark, in tree hollows. Maintain fire constantly (wet fuel smokes heavily).','INSECTS: Mosquitoes, leeches, ants, ticks. Cover skin, use repellent if available, check for leeches daily. Sleep under mosquito net.','DISEASE: Malaria, dengue, parasites, bacterial infections. Prevent mosquito bites, purify water, keep wounds clean. Seek medical care if fever or illness develops.']})

E.append({'id':'l1-survival-arctic-basics','title':'Arctic Survival — Cold, Shelter, Fire, Frostbite','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'environment','tags':['arctic','cold','winter','frostbite','hypothermia'],'region_relevance':['boreal','arctic'],'confidence':'high','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11','nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-medical-hypothermia','l1-medical-frostbite'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Arctic survival priorities: stay warm, build insulated shelter, avoid frostbite, maintain fire, conserve energy. Cold (below -20F) kills fast. Wind chill multiplies cold danger. Layered clothing, windproof outer layer, insulated shelter essential.','warnings':['Frostbite can occur in minutes at -20F with wind','Touching metal with bare skin causes instant freeze injury','Wet clothing loses insulation - stay dry or change immediately','Sweating in cold is dangerous - remove layers before overheating'],'steps':['SHELTER: Insulated from ground and wind. Snow cave (dig into snowbank, smooth ceiling to prevent drips), igloo (requires practice), debris hut (see entry). Smaller shelter = easier to heat with body warmth.','FIRE: Essential for warmth, melting snow for water, cooking. Collect large supply of dry wood (wet wood will not burn). Build fire on platform (prevents melting into snow). Keep fire going constantly.','CLOTHING: Layer system. Base (wicking layer - wool or synthetic), mid (insulation - fleece, down), outer (windproof, waterproof). Avoid cotton (loses insulation when wet). Cover all skin (frostbite risk).','WATER: Melt snow or ice (do NOT eat snow - cools body, causes dehydration). Boiling snow for water consumes lots of fuel. Collect ice (less fuel to melt than snow).','FROSTBITE PREVENTION: Cover face, hands, feet. Move fingers and toes regularly. Check for numbness (early frostbite sign). Warm affected areas immediately (skin-to-skin, not fire).','CONSERVE ENERGY: Cold increases calorie needs. Eat high-fat foods. Limit exertion. Sweat cools you dangerously.']})

# Final 5 entries
E.append({'id':'l1-survival-winter-comprehensive','title':'Winter Survival — Cold Weather Clothing, Shelter, Fire','category':'L1_immediate_survival','subtopic':'environment','tags':['winter','cold','snow','hypothermia'],'region_relevance':['temperate','boreal'],'confidence':'high','sources':['nols-wilderness-guide'],'related_entries':['l1-medical-hypothermia','l1-survival-arctic-basics'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Winter survival in temperate climates (0 to -20F). Hypothermia and frostbite are main threats. Layered clothing, insulated shelter, fire, dry socks. Water sources freeze - melt snow. Travel is exhausting in deep snow. Conserve energy.','warnings':['Wet clothing causes rapid hypothermia even in mild cold (40F)','Snow blindness (UV damage to eyes) causes temporary blindness - wear sunglasses or improvise eye protection','Breaking through ice into water is often fatal - test ice thickness, avoid if possible'],'steps':['CLOTHING LAYERS: Base wicking layer, insulation layer, windproof shell. Avoid cotton. Wool and synthetic retain warmth when wet. Hat, gloves, warm boots, extra socks.','SHELTER: Windproof and insulated. Snow provides excellent insulation (pile snow around tent or shelter walls). Small shelters warm faster with body heat.','FIRE: Essential. Gather dry wood (standing dead trees, inner bark). Build fire on platform (prevents melting into snow and extinguishing). Maintain fire constantly - restarting is hard.','WATER: Melt snow or ice near fire. Do not eat snow (cools body). Dehydration is common in winter (cold air is dry).','TRAVEL: Deep snow is exhausting. Use snowshoes or skis if available. Travel on ridges (less snow). Avoid avalanche terrain (see entry).','FROSTBITE: Watch for numb fingers, toes, nose, ears. Rewarm gradually (body heat, warm water). Do not rub (damages tissue).']})

E.append({'id':'l2-food-water-storage-methods','title':'Water Storage — Clean Collection, Long-Term Storage, Rotation','category':'L2_food_biology','subtopic':'water','tags':['water-storage','containers','purification','long-term'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'high','sources':['cdc-water-treatment','usda-food-safety'],'related_entries':['l1-water-purification-boiling'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Store water for emergencies or when municipal supply is unreliable. Clean food-grade containers, treat water before storage (bleach or boil), rotate every 6-12 months. Minimum 1 gallon per person per day for 3 days (emergency kit). Long-term: 30+ gallons per person.','warnings':['Non-food-grade containers (used for chemicals) contaminate water','Algae grows in stored water if exposed to light - use opaque containers','Stored water can harbor bacteria if not treated before storage'],'steps':['CONTAINERS: Food-grade plastic (HDPE #2 or PET #1), glass, stainless steel. Clean thoroughly (bleach solution, rinse). Avoid containers that held chemicals, milk, juice (residue remains).','WATER TREATMENT BEFORE STORAGE: (1) Municipal tap water - no treatment needed (already chlorinated). (2) Well water or untreated source - boil 1 min, cool, then store. OR add bleach (8 drops unscented bleach per gallon, mix, wait 30 min).','FILLING: Fill containers to top (minimizes air, reduces bacterial growth). Seal tightly. Label with date.','STORAGE LOCATION: Cool, dark place. Avoid direct sunlight (promotes algae). Keep off concrete floor (chemicals can leach through plastic - use wood platform or shelf).','ROTATION: Replace stored water every 6-12 months. Use old water for plants, cleaning. Refill with fresh.','LONG-TERM BULK STORAGE: 55-gallon drums (food-grade). Water tanks (500+ gallons) for homesteads. Rainwater cisterns (filter and treat before use).']})

E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-beekeeping-expanded','title':'Beekeeping Expanded — Hive Management, Honey Harvest, Swarm Capture','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['bees','honey','pollination','beekeeping'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['usda-plants-database'],'related_entries':['l4-agriculture-season-planning'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Beyond basic beekeeping - managing hive health, preventing swarming, capturing wild swarms, extracting honey without equipment. Bees provide honey, wax, pollination. One hive produces 30-60 lbs honey per year. Requires weekly inspections during active season.','warnings':['Bee stings can be fatal to allergic individuals - know your allergy status','Aggressive hives (Africanized bees in some regions) are dangerous','Improper hive management leads to swarms (bees leave) or hive death'],'steps':['HIVE INSPECTIONS: Weekly during spring/summer. Check: (1) Queen present (eggs, larvae visible). (2) Adequate food (honey, pollen stores). (3) Pests (varroa mites, wax moths, small hive beetles). (4) Space (add boxes if crowded - prevents swarming).','SWARM PREVENTION: Bees swarm when hive is crowded (colony splits, half leaves with old queen). PREVENT: Add boxes for space, split hive manually (artificial swarm), remove queen cells (where new queens develop).','CAPTURING SWARMS: Wild swarms cluster on branch (20,000 bees in ball). CAPTURE: (1) Shake or brush swarm into box. (2) Leave box near swarm site until evening (stragglers enter). (3) Close box, move to hive location. (4) Transfer into hive boxes. Free bees, fully functional colony.','HONEY HARVEST: Late summer (after nectar flow ends). (1) Remove frames with capped honey. (2) Brush off bees. (3) Cut off wax caps (with knife). (4) Extract honey (centrifuge spinner or crush-and-strain method). (5) Strain, bottle. (6) Leave 60+ lbs honey for bees (winter food).','WINTER MANAGEMENT: Bees cluster for warmth (do not open hive in cold). Reduce hive entrance (keeps mice out). Check weight (lift hive - should feel heavy. Light = feed sugar syrup). Insulate if extreme cold.']})

E.append({'id':'l4-agriculture-aquaculture-basics','title':'Aquaculture Basics — Fish Ponds for Food Production','category':'L4_agriculture_labor','subtopic':'agriculture','tags':['aquaculture','fish','pond','tilapia','catfish'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['usda-food-safety'],'related_entries':['l2-fish-catfish-identification'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Raise fish in ponds for food. Tilapia (warm water, easy), catfish (hardy, fast-growing), trout (cold water). Requires pond (natural or dig), feeding, water quality management. Harvest fish as needed. High protein yield from small space.','warnings':['Fish ponds can attract predators (herons, raccoons, otters) - netting required','Poor water quality (low oxygen, high ammonia) kills fish rapidly','Freezing kills warm-water fish (tilapia) - cover pond or move indoors in winter','Overstocking causes disease and stunted growth'],'steps':['POND CONSTRUCTION: Natural pond (spring-fed, creek) or dig pond (line with clay or plastic liner). Size: 100 sq ft per 10 fish (minimum). Depth 3-4 feet (deeper in cold climates to prevent freezing).','SPECIES SELECTION: TILAPIA - Fast-growing, warm water (70-85F), breed rapidly. Best for warm climates. CATFISH - Hardy, tolerate crowding, cold-tolerant. TROUT - Require cold water (50-60F), high oxygen. CARP - Very hardy, omnivorous, but bony.','STOCKING: Fingerlings (young fish) from hatchery or wild-caught. Stock 1 fish per 10 gallons (conservative). More = faster growth but requires feeding and water management.','FEEDING: Natural food (insects, algae, zooplankton) supports some fish. Supplement with commercial pellets, or grain, vegetable scraps. Feed daily (what they consume in 5 min).','WATER QUALITY: Oxygen essential (aerate with waterfall, fountain, or air pump). Test ammonia (toxic) - change water if high. Algae bloom (green water) indicates nutrients - good for fish but excessive blocks oxygen.','HARVEST: Net fish as needed or drain pond (harvest all). Process like wild fish (gut, cook thoroughly).']})

E.append({'id':'l3-materials-lime-cement-making','title':'Lime & Cement Making — Mortar for Construction','category':'L3_materials_chemistry','subtopic':'materials','tags':['lime','cement','mortar','construction','chemistry'],'region_relevance':['global'],'confidence':'medium','sources':['us-army-fm-4-25-11'],'related_entries':['l3-construction-earth-building','l4-construction-log-cabin'],'last_verified':TODAY,'summary':'Lime (calcium oxide) and cement are binders for mortar and concrete. Lime made by heating limestone (calcium carbonate) to 900C+. Mix lime with sand and water = mortar (binds bricks, stones). Portland cement is complex but lime mortar is achievable with primitive kiln.','warnings':['Quicklime (calcium oxide) is caustic - causes severe burns on contact with water or skin','Slaking lime (adding water to quicklime) produces extreme heat and steam - can explode if water added too fast','Lime dust irritates lungs - work outdoors, avoid inhaling'],'steps':['LIMESTONE: White/gray sedimentary rock (fizzes when acid applied). Common near ancient seabeds.','LIME KILN: Stone-lined pit or stack. Heat limestone to 900-1000C (red-hot glow) for 12+ hours. Limestone chemically changes (releases CO2, becomes quicklime).','SLAKING: Quicklime + water = slaked lime (calcium hydroxide). ADD WATER SLOWLY (sprinkle, do not pour). Mixture heats violently, steams, expands. Let cool and hydrate for days.','LIME MORTAR: Mix slaked lime + sand (3 parts sand to 1 part lime) + water. Result: paste. Spread between bricks or stones. Hardens by absorbing CO2 from air (carbonation). Sets slowly (weeks) but durable.','USES: Mortar for stone/brick walls, plaster for walls, whitewash (thin lime paint - disinfects and reflects light).','CEMENT (advanced): Lime + clay + high heat (1450C). Difficult to achieve primitive. Lime mortar is adequate for most construction.']})

